    "convergence_bound": {
      "claim": "CoalCEGAR converges for safety fragment in finitely many steps",
      "proof_sketch": "The abstraction lattice Lambda has k_max * n_max * L elements. Each refinement step strictly decreases the abstraction triple (k increases, n increases, or eps decreases). Since the lattice is finite and each step is strict, termination follows. For the safety fragment (greatest fixed points), Proposition 1 guarantees monotonicity: satisfaction can only increase under refinement. Combined with lattice finiteness, this gives convergence to the maximal satisfaction degree within at most |Lambda| = k_max * n_max * L steps.",
      "explicit_bound": "At most k_max * n_max * ceil(log(eps_0/eps_min) / log(1/refinement_factor)) steps",
      "empirical_validation": {
        "models_tested": 5,
        "all_converged": true,
        "max_iterations_needed": 2,
        "monotonicity_verified": false
      },
      "honest_limitation": "The bound is on the safety fragment only. For liveness properties, convergence requires the Galois distortion delta(alpha, alpha') < eps_phi at each step, which is not guaranteed in general. We scope this claim explicitly and note that all six specification templates in Table 5 fall within the safety or bounded-liveness fragment."
